5000|$|Australian born artist John Peter Russell {{was a man}} {{of means}} and having married a {{beautiful}} Italian, Mariana Antoinetta Matiocco, he settled at <b>Belle</b> <b>Île</b> off the coast of Brittany where he established an artists' colony.Russell had met Vincent van Gogh in Paris and formed a friendship with him. [...] Van Gogh spoke highly of Russell's work, and after his first summer in Arles in 1888 he sent twelve drawings of his paintings to Russell, to inform him about the progress of his work. Monet often worked with Russell at <b>Belle</b> <b>Île</b> and influenced his style, though {{it has been said that}} Monet preferred some of Russell's <b>Belle</b> <b>Île</b> seascapes to his own. Russell did not attempt to make his pictures known.|$|R
